It depends on how you do the cpomparison, but generally speaking yes. 
Originally I selected random genomes from a species to compare new 
genomes against, but I changed this to always compare with the species 
champ. Now if the champ is always the same genome (or if it doesn&#39;t 
change very often) then the species is more tightly anchored to a 
specific point in the fitness space. Unfortunately whether this actually 
happens depends on the fitness function, e.g. if the it is 
non-deterministic then the best genome may be different at each generation.


&gt;A similar argument applies when mutating individuals from a single 
&gt;species, if the individual is tested first against some species other 
&gt;than the one it came from, then the chances are the second species 
&gt;has been moved closer to the first.
&gt;  
&gt;
Sure, but again I always test against the parent specie(s) first. 
Initially this was a performance optimisation, but it does make [some] 
sense to only put a spawned genome in a different species if it is 
sufficiently different to escape the parent specie(s).

